  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For man also knoweth not his time,.... Though it is fixed and settled by the Lord, yet times and seasons are kept in his own power, and not known by men; not the time of his death, nor of any calamity and distress coming upon him, nor the proper season and opportunity of doing himself good, and avoiding evil; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "as the fishes that are taken in an evil net, and as the birds that are caught in the snare; as fishes are suddenly taken in a net, unhappy for them, which is at once east over them, while they are sporting and playing in the water, and catching at the bait; and as birds, being decoyed, are unawares taken in a snare; that is, both of them know not the time of their being caught; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "so are the sons of men snared in an evil time, when it falleth suddenly upon them; they are no more able to guard against a time of adversity and calamity, and the evil of it, which comes at once upon them, than the poor fishes or silly birds are to avoid the net and snare; and are, like them, at such a time, in the utmost security, indulging themselves in ease and pleasure: so the day of death, and of judgment, will come like a thief in the night; or like a snare upon men, when they think nothing of it, but are giving up themselves to their lusts and pleasures; see 1 Thessalonians 5:2; for pleasure, as Plato says, is the bait of evils, with which men are caught, as fishes with the hook (g). ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "so are the sons of men snared in an evil time, when it falleth suddenly upon them; they are no more able to guard against a time of adversity and calamity, and the evil of it, which comes at once upon them, than the poor fishes or silly birds are to avoid the net and snare; and are, like them, at such a time, in the utmost security, indulging themselves in ease and pleasure: so the day of death, and of judgment, will come like a thief in the night; or like a snare upon men, when they think nothing of it, but are giving up themselves to their lusts and pleasures; see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Thessalonians 5:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; for pleasure, as Plato says, is the bait of evils, with which men are caught, as fishes with the hook (g). ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(g) Apud Ciceronem de Senectute, c. 12. \"Hic ubi saepe occultum visus decurrere piscis ad hamum\", Horat. Epist. l. 1. Ep. 8. v. 73, 74. ",
        "children": [
